AVIAN INFLUENZA (76): LESOTHO (MASERU) POULTRY, FIRST REPORT, HPAI H5, OIE
**************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 31 May 2021
Source: OIE WAHIS [edited]
https://wahis.oie.int/#/report-info?reportId=33994


Highly pathogenic avian influenza, Lesotho
------------------------------------------
General information
Report type: immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 28 May 2021
Date of confirmation of the event: 30 May 2021
Reported on: 31 May 2021
Reason for notification: 1st occurrence in the country
Causal agent: highly pathogenic avian influenza virus
Serotype: H5
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, laboratory
This event pertains to the whole country.

New outbreaks (1)
Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak location 1: Ha Penapena, Maseru
Date of start of the outbreak: 28 May 2021
Epidemiological unit: farm
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered or killed for commercial use / Vaccinated
Birds / 3000 / 816 / 816 / 0 / 0 / 0
Affected population: a mixed farm keeping layers, pigs, indigenous cattle and sheep

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: introduction of new live animals.

Control measures at event level
Domestic control measures applied: traceability, quarantine, screening, official disposal of carcasses, by-products, and waste, official destruction of animal products, disinfection, ante- and post-mortem inspections

Domestic control measures to be applied: zoning, stamping out, movement control inside the country

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Outbreaks / Test / Test date / Result
Central Veterinary Diagnostic Laboratory, Lesotho (national laboratory) / Birds / 1 / Real-time polymerase chain reaction (real-time PCR) / 30 May 2021 / Positive

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

